Ford GoBike System Data Exploration¶

by Michael Utomi Ehiabor¶

Introduction¶

This document explores a dataset with information containing 183,412 individual rides in a bike sharing system covering the greater San Fransisco bay area in 2019

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

There are 183,412 rides in the dataset with 16 features ('duration_sec','start_time', 'end_time', 'start_station_id', 'start_station_name', 'start_station_latitude', 'start_station_longitude', 'end_station_id', 'end_station_name', 'end_station_latitude', 'end_station_longitude', 'bike_id', 'user_type', 'member_birth_year', 'member_gender','bike_share_for_all_trip'). Most Variables are numeric but the variables 'start_time', 'end_time' and 'member_birth_year' have the wrong data types.

The variables 'start_station_id' (197), 'start_station_name' (197), 'end_station_id' (197), end_station_name (197), member_birth_year (8265), member_gender (8265) all contain missing values.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

I am most interested in figuring out:

  1. The average duration of rides taken
  2. The day of the week and time of the day that most trips are taken
  3. The relationship between user types and the answers to the two questions above and if steps can be taken to convert ordinary customers into Subscribers

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

The main features of interest are duration_sec, start_time, user_type. I will be performing feature engineering on the main features of interest to extract the day of the week and time of day from the start_time feature to help answer the second question listed above. The member_gender and member_birth_year will also be very useful in getting more insight about user activity.

#Extract time of the day from start_time
ford_bike_new['start_hour'] = ford_bike_new['start_time'].apply(lambda x: x.hour)

def getTimeOfDay(time):
    hour = time.hour
    if hour >=0 and hour <12:
        return 'Morning'
    if hour >= 12 and hour < 16:
        return 'Afternoon'
    if hour >= 16 and hour <= 19:
        return 'Evening'
    if hour > 19 and hour < 24:
        return 'Night'
    
ford_bike_new['day_time'] = ford_bike_new['start_time'].apply(lambda time: getTimeOfDay(time))
In [12]:
day_order = ['Morning', 'Afternoon', 'Evening', 'Night']
dorder = pd.api.types.CategoricalDtype(ordered = True, categories = day_order)
In [13]:
ford_bike_new['day_time'] = ford_bike_new['day_time'].astype(dorder)
In [14]:

In [30]:
#Group users into different age groups
def useragegroup(user_age):
    if user_age >=10 and user_age <=20:
        return '10 - 20'
    if user_age > 20 and user_age <= 30:
        return '21 - 30'
    if user_age > 30 and user_age <= 40:
        return '31 - 40'
    if user_age > 40 and user_age <= 50:
        return '41 - 50'
    if user_age > 50 and user_age <= 60:
        return '51 - 60'
    if user_age > 60 and user_age <= 70:
        return '61 - 70'
    if user_age > 70 and user_age <= 80:
        return '71 - 80'
    if user_age > 80:
        return '81 and above'
    
ford_bike_new['age_group'] = ford_bike_new['user_age'].apply(useragegroup)

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

The distribution of duration_sec was skewed with a very long tail, I had to to create a new variable for trip duration measured in minutes trip_duration and then I plotted it on a log scale which made the distribution to look unimodal with a peak just under 10 minutes.

The distribution of user_age variable that i was able to create by substracting the member_birth_year from the current year 2023 was also very skewed due to the fact that a huge percentage of user are between the ages of 20 - 40, i treated this by grouping the ages and this resulted in a less skewed plot

The plots for member_gender, user_type, day_of_week, day_time, start_hour were not as complicated and i was able to get the following insights about the dataset from them.

Majority of trips are started between 8-9am and 5-6pm. This makes sense because most people tend to leave for work between 8-9am and leave the office between 5-6pm.

Approximately 89% of the total number of trips (163,544) were taken by subscribers with the remaining 11% (19,868) taken by casual riders. This is not strange because Subscriber are most likely using the rides for their daily movement while causal riders would tend to use the rides for leisure activities.

Almost 75% (130,651) of rides were taken by men while women took approximately 23% (40,844) of the total number of rides. 2% was taken by 'other' gender.

The time of the day with the most trips is in the morning with 70,465 (38.4%) trips taken while night has the lowest with 15605 (8.5%) trips taken. This is expected because of the number of people who are heading to work or have places to be.

Is the average duration of trips taken dependent on the age group of the riders?¶

In [36]:
# Calculate the average trip duration by age group
age_group_trips = ford_bike_new.groupby('age_group')['trip_duration'].mean()

#Convert age_group_trips to a table using reset index
age_group_trips = age_group_trips.reset_index( name = 'average_duration')

#Plot average trip duration vs age group

plt.ylabel('Average Trip Duration (min)')
plt.title('Average Trip Duration By Age Group')
plt.show()

It is normal to expect people who are younger to have the higher average trip duration but from the plot above proves that theory wrong. We can see that people between the ages of 51-80 take longer trips on average, so it is safe to say to trip duration is not dependent on the on the age of individuals.

Let's move on to looking at how user_type and trip duration correlate.

What is the relationship between Trip duration and User type?¶

In [37]:
# Calculate the average trip duration by user type
user_type_trips = np.round(ford_bike_new.groupby('user_type')['trip_duration'].mean(),1)

#Convert age_group_trips to a table using reset index
user_type_trips = user_type_trips.reset_index( name = 'average_duration')

plt.figure(figsize=[8,5])
sb.barplot(data = user_type_trips, x = 'user_type', y = 'average_duration')
plt.xlabel('User Type')
plt.ylabel('Average Trip Duration (min)')
plt.title('Average Trip Duration By User Type')
plt.show()

print(user_type_trips)

    user_type  average_duration
0    Customer              23.9
1  Subscriber              10.7

In the plot above we can see that Customers (23.9 minutes) spent more time on trips on average than Subscribers (10.7 minutes). This might be because Subscribers mostly used the rides for short everyday comutes like going from home to work or to school while Customers might want to use the bikes for recreational activites during the weekends

Lets look at the average trip duration by that day of the week to find out more.

From the bar chart above, we can see that the day of the week that the highest number of trips (Thursday) is not dependent on the user type. The graph also shows that there is a reduction in the number of rides taken by Subscribers on Saturdays and Sundays, this is understandable because a lot of subscribers do not have to go to work during the weekends. As for casaul riders, there is not major change in the number of rides taken on different days of the week.
